 # Sentinel — CKD Between-Visit Agent
### Product Requirements Document · v2.0

**Event:** Abridge × Anthropic × Lightspeed × Cerebral Valley — "Build Agents for Healthcare Clinics"
**Date:** 18 July 2026 · in-person, San Francisco (Shack15) · team ≤ 2
**Status:** Spec to build against in-room (no functional code shipped in advance)
**Guideline basis:** KDIGO 2024 CKD (finalised); KDIGO 2026 Diabetes-and-CKD update noted as direction of travel

---

## 1. One-liner

An agent that runs the between-visit clinical review no clinician has time to run — for one chronic condition, chronic kidney disease. It reasons over a patient's longitudinal record, catches a slow decline that's invisible value-by-value but obvious across years, flags a now-indicated treatment the patient isn't on, produces a prioritised action list plus a draft referral, and — critically — knows what *not* to surface, so a clinician actually trusts it.

## 2. Product vision

Abridge captured the highest-value fifteen minutes in medicine — the visit — and turned the conversation into structured data. But chronic disease isn't managed in the visit; it's managed in the 364 days *between* visits, where today almost nothing happens: no monitoring, no titration, no escalation until the patient deteriorates and shows up in the emergency department. That gap is where the majority of chronic-disease cost and morbidity accrues.

Moya's thesis is that this between-visit layer can be run by an agent: continuously ingesting labs, devices, medications and symptoms; reasoning longitudinally; escalating only what needs a human. This is agentic in the sense that matters — it replaces *labour* (the care-coordinator workflow that doesn't scale), not just assists with a task — and it compounds, because every patient-year of longitudinal reasoning makes the next decision better.

CKD is the ideal first wedge: clear labs, clear guidelines, clear deterioration signals, and a genuine, catchable under-treatment pattern in the real world. The narrow, deep slice implies the platform. Big vision, narrow knife.

## 3. Problem statement

Chronic kidney disease affects roughly one in seven adults, is usually silent until late, and is driven mostly by diabetes and hypertension. Most people with CKD stage 3–4 die of cardiovascular disease before they ever reach dialysis, which makes CKD a cardiovascular risk multiplier as much as a kidney problem. Three specific failures happen between visits:

The **slow decline goes unseen.** An eGFR falling ~6 mL/min/year looks "normal-ish" at every single visit; no one is fitting the trend across years, so the patient crosses into a high-risk stage unnoticed.

The **now-indicated drug is never started.** The clearest real-world example is the non-diabetic albuminuric patient who qualifies for an SGLT2 inhibitor but was never started, because the drug is still mentally filed under "diabetes." This is a cardiorenal-protective drug the patient should be on and isn't.

The **existing tools cry wolf.** Naive rule engines flag every dip and every gap, including the ones that are benign or unsafe to action, so clinicians stop trusting them and switch them off. The scarce resource is not detection — it's *trustworthy* detection.

## 4. Goals & success metrics

The product goal is a clinician-usable between-visit review for a CKD panel. The hackathon goal is to win the room. Both are served by the same build, and the metrics below map deliberately onto the judging rubric.

| Rubric dimension (approx. weighting) | What we must show | How this PRD delivers it |
|---|---|---|
| Impact (~20%) | A real pain point at scale | Between-visit review across a whole patient panel, not one chart |
| Technical complexity (~20%) | Genuinely engineered, not if-statements-plus-a-chatbot | Real agentic loop planning and calling deterministic tools; longitudinal reasoning; an eval harness as evidence of rigour |
| Clinical credibility | Something a clinician could use Monday | Deterministic guideline core with testable thresholds; human-in-the-loop; drafted (not sent) referral |
| Originality | Not a banned pattern | Deterministic guideline encoding + a suppression layer no generic wrapper builds — explicitly *not* RAG |

Concrete success criteria for the demo: the agent triages a small panel; surfaces exactly three prioritised items on the hero patient; produces a draft referral; and shows a suppression panel of what it considered and deliberately withheld, each with a one-line reason. The eval harness reports correct surfaces and correct suppressions against a scored gold set.

